et MS'; font-size:10pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">UK-GBC </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">agrees </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">that where appropriate, standards should be brought into Building Regulations</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> as soon as possible. However this is not a solution that works for all issues. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">We believe that suitable transitional arra</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ngements must be put into place while elements of the Code for Sustainable Homes (CSH) are phased out and until new regulations are in place.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">One of the key functions of the CSH was to set out the direction of travel for Building Regulations. In our view it has been helpful to have a sense of what best practice looks like that developers can and should aspire to. </span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">e </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">strongly </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">agree with the Challenge Panel's assertion that standards for daylight,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> sunlight, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ventilation</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> and materials</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> should be more thoroughly investigated</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> and brought in to regulation</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Daylighting, sunlight and ventilation are all intertwined and must be considered as a whole. </span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">General comments</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">UK Green Building Coun</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">cil (UK-GBC) is an independent, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">mem</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">bership-based</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">charity</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> committed to radically improving the sustainabil</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ity of the built environment by </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">transforming the way it is planned, designed, constr</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ucted, maintained and operated. We have around 400 members from across the property and construction sector, including house builders, local authorities, Registered Providers and product manufacturers. UK-GBC was on the steering group for the Housing Standards Review technical committee.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">It is UK-GBC’s view that the time was right for a review and rationalisation of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the current range of voluntary standards applied to new homes. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">However, we have always maintained that the changes must support deliver</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">y of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">high quality sustainability homes </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">that are </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">fit for the future. W</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ith the demise of the CSH and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">omissions </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">in the Housing Standards Review consultation </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">around issues like materials, we risk losing a momentum that has transformed the way homes have been built over the last seven years.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">UK-GBC </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">agrees </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">that where appropriate, standards should be brought into Building Regulations</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">. However, we believe that this process should happen</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> as soon as possible, and we do not believe that th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">e government's self imposed 'o</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ne in two out' rule is a valid excuse to delay action.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">One of the key functions of the CSH was to set out the direction of travel for Building Regulations. In our view it has been helpful to have a sense of what best practice looks like that developers can and should aspire to, and in the absence of the CSH the onus will be on the industry to drive innovation and best practice. Some developers have embraced sustainability and are innovating and achieving impressive sustainability standards. For them, there are elements of the CSH that were deeply frustrating, because inevitably the CSH is prescriptive. However, the industry has a ‘long tail’, with many companies who are either not interested in sustainability, or not able to carry out the necessary research and development to innovate. We need a new kind of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">sustainability framework which allows the leaders to keep pushing the boundaries, but also provides the guidance and drivers to act for the rest of the industry. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">We believe that suitable transitional arrangements must be put into place, and where </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Local Planning Authorities (</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">LPAs</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> already have higher standards in place </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">which have been tested through due process and accepted as viable, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">they should be allowed to keep those higher requirements until the new regulations take over (e</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">g</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> Part L 2016). There is no sense in weakening requirements which are</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> already</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> being met, only to raise them again in 2-3 years.  </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Comments on specific issues:</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Energy</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">We strongly support the zero carbon 2016/2019 policies, and we agree that fabric energy efficiency standards are the domain of national standards and so we broadly support the approach outlined in the consultation document. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">However, t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">here is always going to be an interplay between building regulations and planning on energy issues. Building regulations should take care of fabric efficiency, onsite carbon compliance and Allowable Solutions, but plann</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ers</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> should have input into the renewable energy strategy for the development. We agree that the rather blunt 'Merton rule' approach, whereby a percentage of renewable energy is required, is </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">usually not the right approach. However, we agree that where viable, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">L</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">As should be able to require developers to link up to</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> low carbon or</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">renewable energy </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">schemes where they exist,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> or will exist in the future,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> as part of a borough wide plan for low carbon and renewable energy.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">here are </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">energy related issues</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">which are currently in the CSH, but not </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">in the proposed new standards. These include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">3.3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Drying space – this is a key element to provide healthy internal environments in the context of increasing air tightness. The Code requires clothes drying provision within the bathroom and the space be mechanically ventilated </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">with a humidistat control. This issue should be taken account of in </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Building Regulations Part F.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">3.3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Energy efficient white goods</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">. Our </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">members’ </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">experience is that the Code does </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">impact on </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">efficiency of the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">white goods which are installed in dwellings.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> Low efficiency white goods are, unfortunately, still available</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> There is a role for tighter product regulation here.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Indoor</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> Environmental Standards</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">We agree with the Challenge Panel's assertion that standards for daylight, sunlight and ventilation should be more thoroughly investigated.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Daylighting, sunlight and ventilation are all intertwined and must be considered as a whole. The tools for assessing these matters should also be reviewed. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Linked to the above, the issue of overheating is a real concern as new homes become more airtight. The government’s response to the issue has so far been inadequate, despite the fact that private sector guidance exists on this issue - for example</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> CIBSE Guide TM52 sets overheating standards. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">UK-GBC believes that </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">SAP should</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> be improved to better</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> address this issue as a matter of urgency</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> – as recommended by the Zero Carbon Hub</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> 3 years ago.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Water</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Since the upper standard of 105 l/p/d + 5l external use is achievable at no/minimal extra cost, we think this should be the baseline standard for all new homes. Our members are meeting this standard on new homes as a matter of course, at no extra cost.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> Code level 5 (80 l/p/d) is usually not viable, apart from in exceptional circumstances. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">In future there could be scope for 'allowable solutions' type approaches for water, but that approach would need to be developed at a national level.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Materials</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">We st</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">rongly disagree with leaving considerations about m</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">aterials to the market</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">. While we recognise that EU policy is beginning to address these issues through standards like CEN TC350, we still feel that there’s a need for national driver to encourage the procurement of healthier and more sustainable construction materials</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">. This is perhaps the biggest omission in the proposed new Housing Standards.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Issue</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">s such as</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> responsible sourcing, toxicity, Ozone depleting potential, and off-gassing of materials in air-tight homes should be addressed as a matter of urgency through new guidance and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> through Building R</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">egulation</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The HSR process was </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">inadequate when it came to considering materi</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">als. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">A materials expert group should be set up as soon as possible to advise on this matter and where best in the regulations these issues should be addressed.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Other issues</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Ecology</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">It is not clear from the consultation document what the proposals are for dealing with the ecology credits from the CSH. Indeed, the issue of ecology is not mentioned at all. We think the CSH has spurred developers into thinking more about ecology at the design stage, and would not want to see its importance downgraded with the demise of the CSH. We agree that ecology is a planning issue, and we think the government should make clear that in the absence of the CSH, all LPAs should have clear policies for improving the ecological value of land through development, as part of their local plan</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">3 October 2013</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="vertical-align:top; width:42.9pt"><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><sp